\section{Monte Carlo Simulation Study}

In our Monte Carlo simulation study, we explored the finite sample performance of the delta and MC methods for CI estimation. The MC method involved generating $20,000$ drift matrices $\boldsymbol{\Phi}$ for each application. We compared these approaches across varying sample sizes (ranging from $50$ to $500$), different time intervals ($\Delta t$ values from $1$ to $30$), and various magnitudes of direct, indirect, and total effects as a result of varying the time intervals. Our model parameters were based on the ``benchmark'' example from \textcite{Deboeck-Preacher-2015}, which exhibits a suppression effect or inconsistent mediation \parencite{MacKinnon-Krull-Lockwood-2000, Shrout-Bolger-2002}, where the direct effect has the opposite sign as the indirect effect. We focused on assessing differences in the delta and MC methods' performance in quantifying uncertainty within a mediation context, considering coverage probability, statistical power, and Type I error rates for the CIs.

