\section{Empirical Example}

In this section, we explored the application of a CT mediation model using empirical experience sampling data from an individual with a history of major depressive disorder. Specifically, we estimated the CT-VAR drift matrix $\boldsymbol{\Phi}$ and the sampling covariance matrix. These estimates allowed us to generate CIs using both the delta and MC methods. Our primary focus was on examining direct, indirect, and total effects within a model that investigates associations between physical discomfort, negative affect, and self-esteem.

Pain, although ultimately a subjective and private phenomenon, is invariably described in terms of sensory and affective properties. This underscores the critical role of emotions in understanding the consequences of chronic pain. Emotional distress is commonly observed in individuals experiencing chronic pain. Numerous studies have demonstrated a significant relationship between emotions and pain intensity, unpleasantness, affective components of pain, and emotional distress among chronic pain patients and their families \parencite{Engel-1977, Jensen-Turk-2014, Gatchel-Peng-Peters-etal-2007}.

Our specific interest lies in exploring how physical discomfort impacts self-esteem through negative affect. Living with chronic pain can exacerbate negative affect, which, in turn, diminishes feelings of self-worth. Individuals dealing with pain often find it challenging to cope effectively, leading to a complex interplay between emotional states and their overall well-being. When individuals experience chronic pain, their ability to accomplish daily tasks diminishes. Whether due to physical limitations or discomfort, they find themselves unable to perform as they once did or as they desire. This persistent struggle can lead to feelings of inadequacy and unproductivity, gradually eroding self-esteem over time. The connection between pain and self-esteem is intricate, influenced by indirect factors such as negative affect. From a CT mediation perspective, we hypothesize that heightened physical discomfort levels correlate with increased negative affect. Consequently, this emotional burden impedes the return of self-esteem to its equilibrium or mean value.

To explore the dynamic interplay between physical discomfort and self-esteem as mediated by negative affect, we explored an empirical data set originally published by \textcite{Wichers-Groot-Psychosystems-2016} and utilized for secondary analysis by \textcite{Kossakowski-Groot-Haslbeck-2017} and in a CT mediation context by \textcite{Ryan-Hamaker-2021}. The data set comprised of $1,476$ semi-random measurement occasions spanning $239$ days. These measurements were collected from a $57$-year-old male participant with a history of major depressive disorder. The participant responded to queries multiple times a day. The time intervals between measurement occasions varied, with a minimum of 13.5 minutes and a maximum of 42.1 hours. We focused on the following variables: physical discomfort, negative affect, and self-esteem. For physical discomfort, we created a composite score for the following items: ``I am hungry'', ``I am tired'', ``I am in pain'', ``I feel dizzy'', ``I have a dry mouth'', ``I feel nauseous'', ``I have a headache'', and ``I am sleepy''. For negative affect, we created a composite score for the following items: ``I feel restless'', ``I feel agitated'', ``I worry'', and ``I can concentrate well'' (reversed). Finally, for self-esteem, we created a composite score for the following items: ``I like myself'', ``I am ashamed of myself'' (reversed), ``I doubt myself'' (reversed), and ``I can handle anything''. All items were measured using a 7-point Likert scale, and the means of these items were calculated to create the composite scores.

\subsection{Data Preparation}

Before delving into the analysis, we followed a specific data preparation procedure, building upon the approach outlined by \textcite{Ryan-Hamaker-2021}. We created a vector of time values by considering the smallest and largest observed values ($0$ and $5724.554$, respectively). These time values were incremented by $0.10$. The newly generated time vector was appended to the existing empirical time vector. We sorted the combined time vector and any duplicated time values were removed. If a time value from the new time vector existed in the original data set, we labeled the observations accordingly. For time values not present in the original data set, we inserted missing values.

\subsection{Data Analysis}

We fitted the CT-VAR model using the \texttt{dynr} package. We estimated the drift $\boldsymbol{\Phi}$ and diffusion $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ matrices. Since the variables were scaled before model fitting, we assumed that the centralizing tendency $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ is a vector of zeros. To simplify the model, we did not estimate the measurement model. Leveraging the estimated drift matrix $\boldsymbol{\Phi}$ and the corresponding sampling variance-covariance matrix, we calculated the direct, indirect, and total effects of the model where the association between self-esteem and physical discomfort is mediated by positive affect using the \texttt{cTMed} package. We examined the mediated model across a range of time intervals (from $> 0$ to $15$). CIs were estimated using the delta and MC methods.

\subsection{Empirical Example Results}

The estimated CT-VAR parameters are presented in Table \ref{tab:manCTMed-empirical-1}. The direct and total effects were not significant for the time intervals we investigated. The indirect effect was significant for time intervals greater than $0.6$ and less than $3.4$ for the delta method, and for less than $8.70$ for MC. The results are presented in the first two rows of Figure \ref{fig:manCTMed-empirical}. Furthermore, we plotted the trajectories of the variables without process noise in Figure \ref{fig:manCTMed-empirical-trajectory}. We modified the estimated drift matrix $\boldsymbol{\Phi}$ by setting paths that were not statistically significant to zero to aid in interpretation. For the direct effect trajectory, the drift matrix was further modified by setting coefficients that originated from or went into the mediator (negative effect) to zero except for the auto effect for the mediator. For the indirect effect trajectory, the drift matrix used was the difference between the initial drift matrix and the drift matrix used for the direct effect trajectory. The auto effect of the mediator was added back to the drift matrix for the indirect effect trajectory to maintain stability. We set the initial values at $t_0$ to construct a hypothetical scenario with high initial physical discomfort and negative affect, and low initial self-esteem to highlight how quickly self-esteem was projected to return to the mean with an increase in physical discomfort in the presence and absence of the indirect effect through negative affect. It can be seen that in the absence of an indirect effect (direct effect trajectory), self-esteem reached the mean quickly. Whereas, when the direct effect was removed and only the indirect effect was driving the trajectory (indirect effect trajectory), the return of self-esteem to its mean was slower. This suggests that high physical discomfort leads to a slower return to the mean for self-esteem as mediated by the high negative affect value.

